<paragraph blockId="28.[160,1155,1234,1364]" box="[160,409,1234,1260]" pageId="28" pageNumber="293">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,409,1234,1260]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="293">External morphology</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="28.[160,1155,1234,1364]" pageId="28" pageNumber="293">Body elongate, narrow, background colour white with longitudinal dark red lines on dorsum and lateral body parts. Cerata long, smooth; background colour green with white punctuation, dark red vertical lines, pink on tips.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="28" pageNumber="293" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="28.[160,1156,1416,1581]" box="[160,252,1416,1442]" pageId="28" pageNumber="293">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,252,1416,1442]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="293">Ecology</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="28.[160,1156,1416,1581]" pageId="28" pageNumber="293">
Specimens were found feeding on the green alga 
<taxonomicName authority="(Roth) Kutzing, 1843" authorityName="Kutzing" authorityYear="1843" baseAuthorityName="Roth" box="[704,1152,1452,1477]" class="Ulvophyceae" family="Cladophoraceae" genus="Cladophora" kingdom="Plantae" order="Cladophorales" pageId="28" pageNumber="293" phylum="Chlorophyta" rank="species" species="prolifera">
<emphasis box="[704,924,1452,1477]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="293">Cladophora prolifera</emphasis>
(Roth) Kützing, 1843
</taxonomicName>
. The egg mass is whitish, cylindrical, found associated with algae. The specimen observed in 2019 was found at night crawling over algae, while the 2017 specimens were hidden inside algae. This could mean that slugs are mostly nocturnal, hiding among algae during the day.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
